Replaces the Nans¶

Makes the missing data easier to work with

Replaces the numeric with zeros, The numeric columns are most likely 0 because they are probably minor or unreported

Replaces the string values with unknown, the unknown string is already in the columns, so this will already be present in the column

Makes new columns¶

Makes the population a function of distance from the nearest gazeteer location. A gazeteer is a directory / dictionary of locations on a map.

I did this to simulate population density of the area.

If gazeteer distance is less than 1 then it is fixed to one, so that a small distance won't result in an $\infty$ population

$$fixed population = \frac{admindivisionpopulation}{gazeteerdistance}$$

Also combines the fatality and injury counts so there is just one casualties column

In [23]:
landslides['r_distance_multiplier'] = np.where((1 / landslides['gazeteer_distance']) > 1, 1, 1 / landslides['gazeteer_distance'])

Tries some initial model making¶

The null hypothesis is 76.4%, this means that if you were to predict 0 for all values it would be 76.4% correct.

First tries a K Nearest Neighbor because to try to see if there is some thing there.

Then tries a cross validation with linear regression, it looks like the cross validation score is about 0.

In [29]:
casualty_free = landslides[landslides['casualties'] == 0].count()['casualties']
null_hypothesis = casualty_free/11033

print(f'The percentage of zeros in the casualties column is {null_hypothesis*100:.2f}%')

The percentage of zeros in the casualties column is 76.40%

In [34]:
scores = []
for k in range(1,50):
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, shuffle=True)
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    knn.fit(X_train,y_train)
    score = knn.score(X_test, y_test)
    scores.append([k, score])
In [35]:
data = pd.DataFrame(scores,columns=['k','score'])
data.plot.line(x='k',y='score');
In [36]:
lr = LinearRegression()

lr.fit(X_train, y_train)
test_score = lr.score(X_test, y_test)


cvs = cross_val_score(LinearRegression(), X, y, cv=KFold(3, shuffle=True))

print(f'Linear regression might not work the score on the test set is {test_score:.2f},\n\
and with cross validation is mean: {cvs.mean():.2f}, max: {cvs.max():.2f}, and min: {cvs.min():.2f}')

Linear regression might not work the score on the test set is -0.26,
and with cross validation is mean: -0.06, max: 0.00, and min: -0.16

Conclusions¶

I don't see any coorelations in the data, from the inital models and seaborn.

If I'm going to move forward, I'll probably need to undersample, which can cause other problems with the data.
